[1] Cholera - Malaysia (Sabah)
Date: Sat 27 Jun 2020 16:36 MYT
Source: The Star [edited]
https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/06/27/four-sabah-districts-hit-by-cholera-outbreak-says-state-health-director


A one-year-old baby is among 14 people hit by a cholera outbreak in 4 Sabah districts due to suspected contamination of water and food, with the reopening of almost all sectors.

Sabah Health Department director Datuk Dr. Christina Rundi said that 10 cases were reported in Kota Kinabalu, 2 in Putatan, 1 each in Tuaran and Semporna between 29 May 2020 and 25 June 2020. Apart from the baby, the oldest person infected by the disease was an 80-year-old, while the rest were between 7 and 18 years old, she said.

Dr. Rundi noted that there was a 75% downward trend of cholera cases during the movement control order (MCO), as compared with the same period in 2019. However, she said that the number of cases has increased, especially with the reopening of almost all sectors, due to food and water contamination. Among the reasons, she said, bacterial infections occurred when eating raw or uncooked food and not cleaning utensils with treated water.

Cholera symptoms include diarrhoea and could be fatal if not treated, particularly among children and babies, due to loss of body fluids.

Urging people to maintain high standards of hygiene, Dr. Rundi said that bacterial infections could spread in areas that do not have a clean water supply, poor toilet facilities and places with poor cleanliness. "We advise the public to always practise preventive measures by drinking boiled water, washing hands before eating or handling food and after going to the toilet," Rundi said, adding that seafood and meat should be properly cooked.

[Byline: Muguntan Vanar]

